know work into your books?

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:26.660
&gt;&gt; Marisha Pessl: Yes, so I --
well so, I grew up with a mom

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:27.960
who was obsessed with
classical cinema.

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:29.260
So when my friends were out like
at a normal movie theater my mom

00:29:29.260 --> 00:29:30.560
and I would be watching
like Turner classic movies

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:31.860
and I would be watching like
Howard Hawks and Preston Sturges

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:33.160
and His Girl Friday and
obsessed with Cary Grant

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:34.460
and Jimmy Stewart,
Alfred Hitchcock.

00:29:34.460 --> 00:29:35.760
So that was another way
for me to really get

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:37.060
through my adolescence
was you know loving these

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:38.360
like old movies where
people had shoulder pads

00:29:38.360 --> 00:29:39.660
and cigarette holders and
James Cagney and all these

00:29:39.660 --> 00:29:40.960
like crazy characters.

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:42.260
So certainly like, you know,
like all influences in childhood

00:29:42.260 --> 00:29:43.560
like that will play out in
one's art in different ways.

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:44.860
Certainly with Night Film the
original, the originating idea

00:29:44.860 --> 00:29:46.160
for that was really
Stanley Kubrick and reading

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:47.460
about the behind-the-scenes
behavior that he really exerted

00:29:47.460 --> 00:29:48.760
on his surroundings,
all in the name of art.

00:29:48.760 --> 00:29:50.060
And the sort of various
means of torture

00:29:50.060 --> 00:29:51.360
that different actors would
sign up for simply to be

00:29:51.360 --> 00:29:52.660
in a Kubrick film and I just
found that so interesting.

00:29:52.660 --> 00:29:53.960
Why were people allowing
themselves to be treated

00:29:53.960 --> 00:29:55.260
like this, was it for the
fame, was it to get outside

00:29:55.260 --> 00:29:56.560
of their day-to-day existence,
which maybe was dreary

00:29:56.560 --> 00:29:57.860
and they wanted to go
off to sort of adult camp

00:29:57.860 --> 00:29:59.160
and have some sort
of experience?

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:00.460
So I really started reading

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:01.880
about these you know
usually male film directors

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:05.080
and how they were
allowed and able

00:30:05.080 --> 00:30:08.520
to like create art,
an art that we love.

00:30:08.520 --> 00:30:12.040
I mean I love Alfred Hitchcock
and then it subsequently come

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:15.560
out as to how he actually
treated people behind the set,

00:30:15.560 --> 00:30:17.140
so behind-the-scenes.

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:20.080
So really, that was
my originating idea.

00:30:20.080 --> 00:30:23.390
So certainly, my childhood
was all about books and movies

00:30:23.390 --> 00:30:27.870
but you know books that's my
centerpiece, that's my love.

